{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FwQVz6NFAZRr4GApv3j5Yk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The StatefulSet mounts the `mongod-config` ConfigMap at `/etc/mongo-config/mongod.conf` using a `subPath`. This is important because with `subPath`, the mounted file does NOT automatically update when the ConfigMap changes - the pod needs to be restarted for the new config to take effect.\n\nAlso importantly, the StatefulSet uses `podManagementPolicy: Parallel`, but the `updateStrategy` is `RollingUpdate` with `partition: 0`, which means a rolling update (restart one pod at a time).\n\nNow let me read the admin password to be able to connect to MongoDB.\n\nMy plan:\n1. First restore the `mongod-config` ConfigMap with the updated values from the backup (verbosity: 1 → 2, slowOpThresholdMs: 200 → 400, journalCompressor: zlib → zstd).\n2. Then trigger a rolling restart of the StatefulSet one pod at a time, since the config is mounted with subPath and requires pod restarts to take effect.\n3. After the rolling restart completes, verify the new config is applied across all members.\n\nSince the ConfigMap is currently empty, I need to apply the correct config before any pod restarts, otherwise they'll fail to start. The sequence is: verify the backup ConfigMap is canonical, apply the updated ConfigMap, confirm it looks correct, trigger the rolling restart, then verify the pods come up with the new configuration. I should also grab the admin password first so I can verify the MongoDB configuration after the rollout.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2376,"cache_read_input_tokens":29991,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2376},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_